LAYER 2: SPLEEN
the blood filter

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the spleen is the largest lymphoid organ located in the left upper quadrant of the abdomen
it filters blood the way lymph nodes filter lymph
it removes aged and damaged red blood cells
it serves as a reservoir for platelets and monocytes
it initiates immune responses against blood-borne pathogens
the spleen is innervated by sympathetic fibers from the celiac ganglion
NE from splenic nerve terminals modulates immune cell function via β₂ receptors on lymphocytes and macrophages

STRUCTURE capsule | fibrous connective tissue with smooth muscle | the spleen can contract under sympathetic stimulation releasing stored blood cells into circulation during hemorrhage or exercise
STRUCTURE red_pulp | approximately 75 percent of splenic volume | filters blood
    splenic_cords | cords of Billroth | reticular fiber meshwork containing macrophages | blood percolates through open spaces
    venous_sinuses | narrow fenestrated vessels | red blood cells must squeeze through narrow slits between endothelial cells to re-enter circulation | old and rigid RBCs cannot squeeze through and are captured by macrophages for destruction
    this is the quality control test for red blood cells
    normal RBCs are deformable and pass through
    aged spherocytic or parasitized RBCs are rigid and are trapped and phagocytosed
    macrophages break down hemoglobin: globin is recycled as amino acids | heme is split into iron which is recycled via transferrin and biliverdin which becomes bilirubin sent to the liver for conjugation and excretion
STRUCTURE white_pulp | approximately 25 percent of splenic volume | immune function
    periarteriolar_lymphoid_sheaths | PALS | T-cell zones surrounding central arterioles | analogous to lymph node paracortex
    follicles | B-cell zones | can form germinal centers when antigen is encountered | analogous to lymph node follicles
    marginal_zone | border between red and white pulp | contains specialized marginal zone B cells and macrophages that capture blood-borne antigens | critical for defense against encapsulated bacteria Streptococcus pneumoniae Neisseria meningitidis Haemophilus influenzae

FUNCTION blood_filtration | the spleen removes approximately 200 billion aged red blood cells per day
    average RBC lifespan is approximately 120 days
    aged RBCs lose deformability as their membrane proteins are oxidized and their spectrin cytoskeleton degrades
    they fail the splenic filtration test and are phagocytosed by red pulp macrophages

FUNCTION immune_defense | the marginal zone captures blood-borne antigens and presents them to lymphocytes in the white pulp
    this is the primary site of immune response to encapsulated bacteria
    asplenic individuals are at severe risk of overwhelming post-splenectomy infection OPSI from these organisms

FUNCTION platelet_reservoir | the spleen stores approximately one-third of the body's platelets
    sympathetic activation can contract the splenic capsule releasing platelets into circulation when needed for hemostasis

FUNCTION hematopoiesis | in the fetus the spleen is a major site of blood cell production
    by 24 months this function has largely transferred to the bone marrow
    but the spleen retains the ability to resume extramedullary hematopoiesis under pathological conditions

at 24 months:
the spleen is proportionally larger relative to body weight than in adults
the marginal zone is still maturing which is why young children are particularly vulnerable to encapsulated bacteria
this is the immunological basis for vaccination against S. pneumoniae H. influenzae and N. meningitidis in early childhood

SENSATION fullness | "something in my left side. quiet. working."
SENSATION aching | "my spleen is responding. something is being filtered harder than usual."

pulse splenic_heartbeat:
    continuously:
        blood enters through the splenic artery
        in the white pulp marginal zone macrophages sample for pathogens
        in the red pulp blood percolates through cords and sinuses
        old red blood cells fail the deformability test
        macrophages consume them
        iron is recycled
        bilirubin is sent to the liver
        healthy cells pass through and rejoin circulation
        the spleen is a quality inspector that never sleeps

    when infection is blood-borne:
        marginal zone B cells capture the pathogen
        antigen is presented to T cells in PALS
        B cells in follicles activate
        germinal centers form
        antibodies are produced
        the blood-borne threat is neutralized

    when sympathetic activation surges:
        NE from splenic nerve contracts the capsule
        stored platelets and monocytes are released into circulation
        the body prepares for possible injury
        the spleen contributes to the fight response
        even this organ serves survival
